I can't get enough of this stretch at the moment 😁 perfect way to open up the shoulders and instantly give you a posture boost! ✨☺️✨ 1⃣Make sure your fingers are pointing toward your toes 2⃣Walk you hands back until you feel a little stretch in the shoulders 3⃣Take a deep breath in and lift the chest 4⃣Breath out & start to bend your elbows, feel the stretch increase 5⃣Go even deeper by squeezing the elbows together behind you.

Rainy days in Sydney 💦💦 calls for a little morning home butt workout! I am going to start focusing on glute exercises to help with my running and sprints. Reverse leg lifts are a great little exercise you can quickly do each morning.
I do a set of 20 left leg then right leg, then 15 then 10 then 5. Only takes a couple of minutes and if I have a bit more time, I rest for a couple minutes and then build up the repetitions (5 each leg, then 10, 15, 20) kind of like a roller coaster down and up again! 🎢 ❗️be careful to only lift you leg as high as you can with a straight lower back (stop lifting if you begin to arch or twist your hip up) keep both hip bones pointing toward the ground during the whole exercise ⬇️⬇️😊 It's time to build that booty!! 👊

Being an egg 😜🐣 My number one tip for getting flexible is CONSISTENCY. Stretching everyday is the best way to teach you body new ranges of movement. The more your body is exposed to something, the more it adapts. I sometimes stretch twice a day. Even 15min each session helps a lot, if you do it EVERYDAY. Set an alarm to get you motivated ⏰ and keep at it! Happy stretching fam! 😘💗

Testing my core with some balance exercises this morning! 😝🔵🙌🏼 A great way to test your core is actually the humble plank! (or push up position)...no, you don't have to try my balancing act! Haha👆🏼😜
When you plank, your abs, obliques and tiny muscles around your spine 'switch on' 💡to support your lower back. A strong plank will improve EVERY exercise you do in your workouts simply because you will have stronger, more stable, and safer movements! (Think of your core as the roots of a tree, giving you a stable base🌳💪🏼)
So let's test your plank today! How long can you hold it WITHOUT sagging in you lower back and losing technique? ⏰😃👊🏼

Back home at my park, and back into my fitness antics!! 😝🌳🔵 haha
I've always said it, but I believe fitness should be fun! 😁 Yes, you need to put in the hard work, train correctly, and make it challenging...but it doesn't need to be torture!! Sometimes, your tastes change and you might prefer one style of exercise for a little while...then another some time later, and that's ok! We can't love the same thing all the time (sometimes we can 😜) ...I always love bodyweight training, but for the last few weeks I'v been mixing it up with some long runs with my boyfriend! 👟
So don't be afraid to mix it up, swap your training style for a little while, get a friend to train with you, or find some inspo to try something new! Keep it exciting, keep it fresh, and keep having fun!! 😄🙌🏼

RUNNERS!!
👟 Your feet are the first contact in a chain reaction that works up into your ankles, knees, hips & back. A lot of running pain, joint wear & tear, and chronic injury can be prevented by keeping on top of your shoe game ☺️👌
Here's how👇
▪️Every person is different, try every shoe you can & even have a jog in the store (check your stride to see if your ankle/knees roll in when you run, get a feel for the shoe etc etc)
▪️When those niggles & injuries start appearing it might be time to change shoes. Support & absorption decreases the more you run. If you run every day, you may need new shoes after 3/4 months (I use my older shoes for strength workouts/walks etc)
▪️Having 2 pairs & alternating them can increase the life of your shoes (the day or two rest in between lets the foam decompress & bounce back)
▪️Don't put your shoes in the washing machine! It damages the foam & structure
▪️Test your new shoes on a less demanding run (like today I only did 6x 200m medium paced runs with some core exercises in between). You can use this to see how your body pulls up after your run

Good shoes are expensive💰😩 But looking after your body & preventing injuries (& the cost of physios, strapping tape, doctors etc) is definitely worth it in the long run (no pun intended 😜). I'm such a big believer of prevention instead of cure! 👍 I hope this helps fam 🙏

PLANKING! 💪

When I am looking for a core exercise challenge at the end of my session I always turn to this... 1min Plank on hands
1min Side plank on left hand
1min Side plank on right hand
1min Elbow plank
1min Side plank on left elbow
1min Side plank on right elbow

No breaks in between!! 💥

Keep the belly button sucked in to the spine (especially in front plank) if you feel yourself drop down or sag in the back come down. A good starting point is 30seconds each side 😊 🆎❤️x

Charlie really wanted to be in on the action this morning and waddled herself over next to me ☺️ Her first video back after her accident! 💪🏼🎉
I’ve been receiving so many messages about her and I just wanted to say another huge thank you for all the lovely thoughts and wishes for her 🙏🏼
She can’t stand or walk yet (she drags her bum around) but she does some great walking if we help hold her up and balance her ☺️🙌🏼 we’ve been using a little strap around her hips to lift up her hind quarters and make it a little easier for her to learn to use her back legs again, her left leg is getting super strong 💪🏼 but her right (which I call her ‘gimpy leg’ 😝) is a little lazy...the right side of her spinal cord had a lot more damage so it will probably take a while to get it as strong as the left...
BUT she is doing SO WELL, resting lots during the day, enjoying the daily leg massage and physio I give her, and is so happy and back to herself which is all I ever could wish for ☺️ Go Charlie Bear!! 🙌🏼🙌🏼

Hey fam! ☺️ So want to get serious with you for a moment...I know with the fitness and health space becoming so saturated over the last few months, everything starts to get confusing and it's difficult to understand WHAT is the correct thing to do! 😩
I want to take this opportunity to stand up for the professionals in this space that have qualifications and many years of education behind them. Studying the human body and how exercise and food integrates with it is HARD. It takes so much time, effort, and experience to get even a simple understanding of how your body works and how to look after it, let alone how to look after someone else's!
I know this because I have spent numerous years (over 8years now!) at college and university becoming qualified in the science of exercise and exercise physiology, and more recently specially qualified in coaching elite athletes, CrossFit, and yoga. I can tell you it is not an easy ride, nor does the learning ever stop.
I strive to continue to learn and educate myself in this area because I want to be a knowledgeable voice for others. And I know there are so many others like me who have given up many years to be specialists in what they do.
What I want you to get out of this is to know where your information is coming from. Your body is precious, and at the same time so very different than anyone else's...there are many amazing professionals who are dedicated to giving you the best possible information they can from years of learning and experience. And they have learnt in detail about prescribing health measures (exercise, food, treatment etc) to others. Lastly, nobody knows your body better than you. If you are unsure about any recommendation, suggestion, or 'fact', trust yourself to do your own research until you are comfortable with where and who it has come from👌🏼☺️

So I thought I would share some stuff about how I workout and for how long because I've been getting a few questions about it ☺️👟
🔻
My schedule gets pretty hectic, I travel a lot, and I don't like using much equipment or training at the gym (I don't even have a gym membership!!)
It's important my training fits around my busy lifestyle and that I can do it anywhere! ☺️⏰✈️
🔻
During the week, I workout twice a day..BUT for only 20min each time! As soon as I wake up, before breakfast and then in the afternoon, before dinner 🍴
🔻
My sessions are high intensity and they focus on the whole body 💪🏼 (I don't do arm days, leg days etc). And I either workout in my living room, the park (like today!!😜), or in my hotel room...its quick, exciting, and sustainable! and I spend less time training for really great results 👌🏼😁 (twice a day training is not as scary as it sounds!!😉)
🔻
The weekends are my time to do FUN exercise and try new things like tennis, hiking, trampolining, rock climbing etc 😁 and Sunday is my rest!

Lately I've been getting lots of questions about what I eat in a day 🍓🍳🍞🥗 so today I've shared some of my meals in Insta story 😬
I'm a vegetarian and I basically don't aim to cut out anything from my diet (apart from meat 😉), rather I look to eat as much variety and fresh, whole foods as I can 🥕🌽🍅 I'm also not a huge 'snack' person so I usually have 3 square meals (I find this works best for me) and I am definitely a creature of habit with most of my meals being quite similar during the week (avocado on toast, stir fry's, vegetarian burritos, noodle soups, salads etc 😝). YES, I eat dessert (dark chocolate is the go-to! 🍫😬), and I do eat pizza/chips/burgers when I go out for dinner...Food is good. Whether it's good for your body or your soul and we should enjoy it and not feel stressed when it comes to eating.
I don't believe there is one perfect way to eat. Overall balance is key, stay away from overly processed/'man made' ingredients, build a positive relationship with eating, and of course actually listen to your body and how it reacts to what you put in it. Apart from that, you do you ✌🏼

If there's even a slight chance of getting something that will make you happy, risk it. Life is too short, and happiness is too rare.

I've had a few questions from you guys about stretches for the hips. As a runner 🏃👟 my hips are also one of the tightest parts of my body 😩 Here is an awesome stretch that I like to do to gently wake up and lengthen the front of the hip and also the groin 😁

1⃣As a warm up start with the back knee down hands on the inside of the front foot. Open the chest and squeeze the shoulder blades together. Gently push the hips down to the ground.

2⃣Increase the stretch by curling the back toe under and lifting the knee off the ground. Keep the chest up and open.

3⃣For an even deeper stretch (especially the groin), drop back down to the knee, bend the arms and lower down to elbows (you can roll to the outer edge of the front foot) 💗
Perfect little stretch for the end of the day ☺️ ab ❤️ x

Need a fresh and exciting way to kick start your fitness in 2016?! 💪🏼🎉 Don't do it alone!! 👫👭👫
We start

What do you do with muscle soreness?!
😫😫😫
I think we've all felt ridiculously sore after a big training session, especially if you do a lot of explosive, jumping or HIIT training
👟💥
As much as you might not WANT to work those sore muscles the next day, it is really important to at LEAST do a light training session 💪🏼
WHY? 😕
Because you increase the blood flow around your body, sending more oxygen and healing nutrients to improve your recovery (recover quicker!!) AND
your muscles and joints are forced to stretch and stay mobile, which means avoiding stiffness and feeling like you are 100years old for 4days after! Haha 😛👵🏼
REMEMBER‼️
Listen to your body. Start your session gently, make sure you do a good warm up and then you can increase the intensity as you get further into the session if you are able. AND alway add extra stretching at the end!! 🙆🏼

Today's workout for you! 😁💪🏼
I want you to really think about technique today...I am always a huge technique tyrant when I coach my athletes!! 🕵 Good form is what gets you amazing results (and keeps you injury free!), so I wanted you to see this video in real time speed...
4 ROUNDS
👉🏼 20x Walking Lunges > focus on BIG steps forward, weight in your front heel as you stand up, and keep your chest up!
👉🏼 20x Push Ups > Belly button in (no sagging in your lower back, and keep your neck long and head up! (It's a common mistake to drop your head and look towards your feet)..drop to knees if you can keep good technique.
👉🏼 10x Long jumps > land on your whole foot to activate your glutes (not just your toes, you'll get sore knees otherwise!)
👉🏼 x20 Plank Drop to Elbows > same tips as push ups..
Slower reps beats fast sloppy technique 👌🏼 So keep it clean today guys!! ☺️👍🏼
Have a great workout!!

For those of you struggling to stick to your fitness routine (either you've had time off, been in the same workout routine, OR you feel like your workouts aren't exciting and don't challenge you anymore) my best advice is to get back to those active things that you LOVE 🙌🏼 or even used to do when you were little 😬
For me it's gymnastics, but it might be tennis, soccer, ice skating, skiing, karate, dance, rollerblading...
It's ok to get bored of your workouts, it's ok to fall off the wagon and lose motivation, and it's ok to do different fit things every month/well/day 😁
Fitness should never be defined as one type of workout and if anything, change is excellent for your body and mind ✨🙃✨

Some of the most basic things you learn are the most important. Especially when it comes to fitness! 💪🏼
All the crazy thing you see me do have taken time to learn, especially LOTS of time practicing less difficult things! Trying to master good running, plank holds, squats, glute exercises, burpees, crunches, push ups...and the list goes on! 📝 Yes of course I spend time practicing harder skills and moves, BUT what helps me the most are the basics!
Just because something is simple, doesn't mean it's easy....try holding a strong plank position for 3minutes and you'll see what I'm talking about 😐 haha 😜 The basics are what I love to practice (and I practice them everyday!) because I know when I practice and aim to master a basic skill, it helps me achieve a strong, fit and balanced body that can handle the trickier things. Without being good at the basics, the crazy things can't happen!
So the next time you are working out fam, I want you to think about every exercise you do..no matter how basic! Think about how you're doing it, what muscles you should be activating, and most importantly enjoy trying to make every rep the best you can..because mastering the basics, is what helps you achieve all the bigger, bolder things you've got your eyes on! ☺️🙌🏼

ps. This is the gym at my hotel here in Vegas!! My trip schedule changed (I was planning on San Fran) but I am here to see Cirque Du Soleil and the Grand Canyon!! 😱😍 I thought I would give you a circus inspired workout exercise! ENJOY FAM! 😜🎪❤️

💪My GO TO back exercise

STEP 1⃣: Put your arms in a cactus 🌵 position, squeeze your bottom & lift your arms off the ground slightly (squeeze your shoulder blades together)

STEP 2⃣: Keep lifted, extend your arms out, pause for 2sec & return to STEP 1 position

15 REPS : 3 ROUNDS

TIPS
❗️stay lifted for all 15 reps
❗️really squeeze your shoulder blades together when bringing your arms to the bent position
❗️keep your bottom squeezed to support your lower back
❗️if you lose good technique, STOP, then reset and try again
❗️when you get stronger you can add a little weight, ie. 1kg Dumbbells or even a sneaker 👟 in each hand

This is a great exercise to do daily to improve posture! 😊

H A P P Y S A T U R D A Y ☀️

I did this leg exercise in the gym today! Such a great exercise to work your legs and especially glutes 💪🏼😁
👉🏼 Start feet together then take a BIG step to the side
👉🏼 As you plant your foot begin to bend your knee and push your bottom back (like you are sitting on a chair), keep your weight in your heel - this is super important as it activates you glute properly!
👉🏼 Stand up by lifting your chest up, push strongly through your heel and bring you feet back together
👉🏼 Do 10-20 reps on 1 leg, then change sides
3 ROUNDS
Trust me, you'll feel your butt tomorrow!! 😜

👉🏼Shoulder+Back Stretches👈🏼
.
CAT COW 🐱🐮
• Do this first sequence as a warm up. INHALE as you look forward & pull your belly button down. EXHALE as you round your spine & look at your belly button. (10slow breaths)
.
PUPPY POSE 🐶
• Reach fingertips FORWARD, press armpits DOWN & point your sitting bones UP
.
SINGLE SIDE PUPPY POSE
• Press your ear to your bicep & guide the outer edge of your armpit DOWN. Keep reaching your fingertips forward to increase the stretch. (Change sides)
.
UPDOG (or COBRA with bent elbows) 🐍
• Squeeze your bottom to support your lower back.
• Press your fingertips into the ground and pull your shoulders BACK & DOWN (open your chest)
.
REMEMBER TO BREATHE!! In all of these stretches. It's a super common mistake to hold your breath when you stretch your upper body...breathing will help your stretch deeper and make it more comfortable 😌
.
👉🏼👉🏼 Hold each of your stretches and progressions for AT LEAST 10 deep breaths in and out 😌
Happy Stretching!! 😘

💪 PEC STRETCH

This is one of my favourite upper body stretches 😊 I do this one every morning
✅ RELEASES TIGHTNESS in the front of the shoulder
✅ Improves POSTURE (open chest & prevents hunching)
✅ Allows MORE MOBILITY in the shoulder joint

TIPS
❗️Fingers point towards toes
❗️Bend elbows to start stretch
❗️Increase stretch by pressing chest up & squeezing elbows together behind you
❗️ Hold for at least 20sec & repeat 3x (chest releases more each time)

Hey guys! I've had a few questions about exercises to do to prevent a 'hunch' type posture and strengthen back muscles.

This is something I have also had to work on so I thought I would share this exercise... 1⃣ Lay face down, hands just outside your shoulders, elbows pointing towards your feet.
2⃣ Squeeze you shoulder blades together then lift hands and elbows about 5cm from the ground (left picture).
3⃣ Keep shoulder blades squeezed and arms off the ground and extend above your head, arms still 5cm off the ground (right picture).
4⃣ Bend arms and return to position 2 then lower arms down to ground and relax.

This is one rep. I usually do 3x 10reps 😊

One of my fave chin up preparation exercises...Hanging Shoulder Shrugs! 💪🏼 @goodlifehc
This is a great way to build strength in the muscles around the scapula (shoulder blade).
The key is to focus on slowly pulling your shoulders AWAY from your ears and then relaxing and letting your shoulders move towards your ears >> Most pulling exercises should stem from activating the scapula FIRST, then your arm should activate second and continue the movement 😊 exercises like lat pull down, seated rows, one arm rows/pulls and chin ups/pull ups all use this 2 part movement.
Think of your scapula as the anchor of your upper body exercises! ⚓️ the stronger they are the easier, more effective, and safer your training will be! 👊🏼

BURPEES!
Love them 😍 or hate them 😡 either way they are an amazing whole body workout! 💪🏼 Arms, Shoulders, Core..and if you do lots , Cardio! 😉
These are 3 variations I teach for burpees (easiest they to hardest 👍🏼)
The first is great when you are starting out, or have lower back pain/weakness..as you get better, move onto the second then third 😁
When doing variation 2&3 remember these tips! 👇🏼😃
☑️ Jump feet in and out nice and quick! 🐰
☑️ Take a big breath in when you clap at the top 👏🏼
☑️ Keep your core tight (suck your belly button into spine)
☑️ Try to pull your hips up to the sky when you jump your feet in or out (it will help to activate you core and make your Burpee effective and efficient!)
Good Luck guys! 😘

Sore lower back?? 😫
Tight hip flexors are a major cause of lower back pain and stiffness...lots of running, exercises like mountain climbers and high knees, and sitting down for long periods of time (ie. School or Work 📝) tighten your hips and put pressure on your back! 😐
I love this stretch before and after my workouts 😃 (you can also drop the back knee to the ground)
TIPS!!
👉🏼Pull your belly button IN to avoid sagging in your back..this will deepen the stretch
👉🏼Try to point both hip bones forward (like headlights!🔦)
👉🏼Open your chest up to the sky and BREATHE to relax into the stretch ☺️ Hold for at least 10 long deeps breaths to stretch through the stretch reflex
Happy stretching fam! 😘

👉🏼Hip Flexor+Quad Stretches👈🏼
.
KNEELING HIP FLEXOR
• Pull your belly button in, lift your chest & squeeze your butt to push your hips forward.
• lift your arms over head and look up to increase the stretch.
.
LIZARD LUNGE
• Place both hands on the INSIDE of your front foot.
• Pull your chest UP as you INHALE & drop your hips DOWN as you EXHALE.
.
TWISTED LIZARD
• Turn towards your front knee & then reach the same arm back (in this video I turn towards my left, then reach back with my left hand).
• As you INHALE twist further around and lift your chest, as you EXHALE drop your hips to the ground.
.
TWISTED LIZARD + QUAD
*only if you have healthy knees!!*
• Bend your back knee & aim to reach your fingers OVER your toes to get your hand flat on top of your foot.
• Guide your hips DOWN & aim to move your foot to bottom (don't lift your hips!)
.
This stretching sequence is great to do BEFORE the Hamstring + Splits sequence I posted earlier 😊
.
👉🏼👉🏼 Hold each of your stretches and progressions for AT LEAST 10 deep breaths in and out 😌
Happy Stretching!! 😘

So, a common question I get from you guys is 'What do I do during my workouts and how often do I train?' 💪🏼 Basically, I 'workout' everyday...but this doesn't mean I work myself to exhaustion everyday!! 😵
My workouts are different each time I train, one day I might really test my fitness while the next day I will focus more on improving technique, or learning a new skill (I also have 1-2 rest days in the week when I will go for a gentle walk and do recovery like foam roller and stretch/yoga)👌🏼Being fit isn't just about having great stamina..its strength, flexibility, power, skill, coordination and so much more! It's about challenging yourself in different ways..
A relaxing yoga class or trying a few challenging exercises like the ones in this video 🎥😉 will give you just as many benefits as a killer high intensity fitness circuit 👊🏼 It is also completely ok to get bored of one type of exercise and to try something new for a while...your body will usually tell you when it's time to spice it up (ie. I was at the grass track this afternoon doing a bit of running and sprinting (you can't see it in the photo, but there's an athletics track marked on this beautiful grass! 👟😃)...usually when I'm walking around the track in between my sprints it gives me a bit of time to just kind of think random thoughts, and almost think clearer than I usually do ☺️💭 there's barely any people around, no noise apart from the birds, and so much green it's amazing to look at!!
🍃🍃🍃
Today I kind of had a moment where I really began to understand why I love exercise and fitness so much.
As I did my sprints, I felt so empowered and in awe of how much I have taught my body and mind over the years...I know the feeling of being physically strong and capable, to be able to control and guide every movement I make, to mentally push myself to run faster or do one more rep, and to most importantly have moments when I know I can't do something, but stay determined and keep trying, and trying, and trying until I can (even if it takes me 3months!!).
Challenging my fitness has taught me to accept that more often than not, the things that feel physically (and mentally) impossible at this present moment, are not there to stop me, they are there to challenge where I THINK my limits are, and help to prove I am stronger and more capable than I believe ✨

Totally lost your workout routine?? 😑 Here are my top three tips to get back on track:
1️⃣
PLAN. Get a diary or notepad and schedule in your workouts for the week. You will be surprised at how much easier it is to 'find time' to workout if it's all planned out for you! 📒
2️⃣
FIND A BUDDY. Get your mum, friend, sister, parter, kids or even your dog involved in your active life. Even if you just go for a walk together, bike ride, play tennis, or find a local class to go to..it'll get you excited to workout and even catch up on some gossip (or have a one way chat if you're walking your dog! 🐶😉)!
3️⃣
WORKOUT PASSION. Find something active you love to do. Just because you have been going to the gym for a year it doesn't mean you can't change it up once a week with a running group, martial arts class, power yoga, at home workout, or even a circus class! Give your body and mind some fresh exercise goodness and reignite that spark! 🏓🚲⚽️⛸

Now I listen. Now I understand.
And now I am strong

To all my fam who have found their strength & to those still on the journey 💪🏼 Today is about honouring the practise, and most importantly, honouring yourself

Leg lifts!! 💪🏼😵 There's 2 variations here for you fam...the first one is great if you are starting out, try and lower your legs as SLOWLY as you can 😁 then the second one is full leg lifts..
If you haven't done any of these before, don't go overboard the first few time your try them (stick to 1 or 2 sets of 10) Why? Leg lifts are really demanding on your hip flexors, if you go too hard before you're ready you can over work them and get an achey lower back the next day! 😫 So ease into it, build up slowly, and always stretch your hip flexors after! ☺️

Part 3 - Straight Leg Lifts (advanced) this exercise challenges not only your core and hip flexors but also your shoulders and lats. Start with lifting as high as you can and work your way to getting your toes to bar.
TIPS
👉🏼 If you have limited hamstring flexibility you can bend your knees slightly (but work on your stretching because flexibility makes this easier!)
👉🏼 As you lift your legs, think about pushing your shoulders back behind you (pull shoulders away from your ears) this will create better space in front of you to lift your legs.
👉🏼 Always stretch your hip flexors at the end of this workout to avoid developing lower back pain.

Sugar and fruit. 🍇🍓🍊🍋🍏 There's been lots of bad press about the sugar in fruit, so I wanted to let you know my opinion...
Yes, fruit has sugar. But you also have to realise that fruit as a whole food is packed full of fibre and other nutrients that balance out the amount of sugar. Fibre especially helps lessen 'sugar high' effects because it allows food to move effectively through the digestive tract, release sugar more slowly into the bloodstream, and also remove toxins from the body.
Fruit juice however, has had the fibre removed and this can spike your blood sugar (this is why I am not a huge juice drinker).
So my view? Fruit is natural, it's in its whole state, and has so many amazing health improving nutrients! I eat heaps of fruit, it has not made me ever put on weight, and it is a great snack (and even dessert) for my active lifestyle and when I feel like something sweet ☺️ And it is definitely a better alternative to foods with processed white sugar! (Sweets, cakes, and even hidden sugar in packaged foods you might think are healthy!)
Of course your diet is completely individual, so it is up to you to understand how you feel when you eat any type of food and know that it is ok to eat the way that best suits you! 👌🏼

This is a great exercise because you can control how much OR how little assistance you need during your chin up 😁
👉🏼 Kick your feet into your partners hands to make your chin ups easier.
👉🏼 Apply less pressure with your feet or ask your partner to lightly assist to make it more challenging.
👉🏼 Keep your neck long and squeeze your shoulder blades together to activate to correct muscles.
‼️If you are the person assisting MAKE SURE YOU USE YOUR LEGS AND SQUAT! (to avoid overusing or straining your back)

'How long should I hold my stretches?'
👉🏼 This is such a common question I get asked! The longer you can hold a stretch, the better BUT if you are strapped for time I always suggest a minimum of 10 long deep breaths in and out...
The reason you count with breathing is because every time you focus on an out breath it allows your body to relax and send you deeper into the stretch 😊

So last week I posted a video that showed you how you could use a partner to help you with learning chin ups...
This vid is a beginner variation that you can do on your own 😁👆🏼
.
TIPS!!
👉🏼 If you don't have a low bar, use a box to stand on.
👉🏼 Pull your shoulders AWAY from your ears (think 'long neck' 🐢) during the whole exercise...it can be tempting to collapse in your shoulder joint!
👉🏼 Squeeze your lower shoulder blades together to activate your back muscles.
👉🏼 Lower SLOWLY...the slower the better!!

Balancing strength and flexibility 💪🏼
It's not easy training to be strong AND flexi, but it is possible. Think about how much time you spend working out and getting strong...and then think about how much time you spend stretching and getting flexible
🤔
One of my favourite ways to fit in stretching each day (because I know how time-poor we can be!!) is stretching in front of the TV at night! 📺🌙✨
👇🏼
Nighttime stretching is a HUGE bonus because it helps you fall asleep easier and encourages a better quality sleep! (This for all the people reading this who are struggling with sleep issues!! 😴)
Try even just 10minutes tonight before you go to bed...sweet dreams!! 💤💤

••• Hip Stretch •••
My number 1 stretch for:
👉🏼 tight hip flexors (front of your hips)
👉🏼 tight groins (inner thighs)
👉🏼 treating lower back pain
👉🏼 improving your running technique
👉🏼 boosting recovery after training
⏰ Hold each stretch for 10 deep breaths (try to get deeper into the stretch on every OUT breath) 😌
Perfect for those of you who run a lot or sit for long portions of the day (these are things that excessively tighten your hip flexors!!)
Enjoy!

So I've been getting a few questions about handstands after my last video 😃 I thought I would share a couple of my fave handstand exercises to help you guys prepare for getting upside down! 🙂🙃🙂
...
My NUMBER 1 tip for learning handstands is to
'get used to being in your hands!' 🙌🏼 so try to make time each day for hanstand practise! (Even if that just means doing lots of planks and down dogs!)
👇🏼
Exercise 1 & 2 are a great way to start understanding what it's like to be upside down and to get your hands and wrists ready to be your base! 💪🏼 Its especially important to press your fingertips into the ground and spread your fingers wide. This will reduce pressure in your wrist joint 👍🏼
👇🏼
The 3 exercises on the wall (easiest - hardest) are a great way to help with you body position upside down. Always try to aim for a straight line from your hands up! and SQUEEZE EVERYTHING!! 😬
...
In all of these exercises think 'shoulders to ears', so almost like you are trying to create earmuffs with your arms...this will help to create a straighter body line 👌🏼
Stick to the exercises you feel comfortable with and progress only when you've mastered the body shapes of each exercise 😎
NOTE: Use the video on your phone to check your technique!! 😉🎥
Good luck guys! Hope this helps! 😘

Progress 💪🏼 It's so easy to get trapped in thinking your workouts are going nowhere when you don't see any physical progress.
You don't lose your fitness and get out of shape overnight, so why is it ok to pressure ourselves into achieving a perfectly fit body instantly? It doesn't seem fair, but somehow we still do it.
It's time to give yourself a chance. Wether you want to be lean and toned, do 10 push ups in a row, get a killer booty, run 10km without stopping or be able to do 1 chin up without assistance..give yourself a chance to achieve it.
If you are consistent with supporting your progress everyday...little changes will happen everyday. Every workout, every run, every rep, and every minute you spend towards achieving what you want is worth it. You can't see it, but on the inside things are changing, and it is only a matter of time before it shows 💪🏼 Let's smash it this week fam! 👊🏼
You have within you, right now, everything you need to triumph over whatever the world can throw at you 👊🏼

💪 SQUATS

They are the fundamental exercise in most fitness programs 👟 Squats are a great way to build leg strength, especially in the glutes, quads and hamstrings

Here are 3⃣TIPS to get you squating like a pro & firing that 😛🔥booty

1. Keep your weight in your heels and squat down like you are sitting in a chair. This reduces pressure in the knee and activates your glutes

2. Place your feet slightly wider than shoulder width apart and squeeze your knees OUT while squatting down & up. This activates more muscle groups (especially your biggest muscle, the glutes) & makes your squats stronger & more stable

3. Keep your chest up & only go as far down as you can keep good technique. You can hold your hands in front (like me in the pic😊) or hold onto something in front of you (eg. pole) to help you keep your chest up

BEGINNER CHIN UPS 💪🏼
This is one of the most fun and motivational ways to get practicing and perfecting your chin ups ☺️🙌🏼
When doing chin ups, keep your neck long (think turtle neck! 🐢) & squeeze your shoulder blades together..
Partners who are assisting, this is your chance to work your squat technique! Sit back with weight in your heels (like your sitting in a chair), back straight, head up!
TIPS!!
👊🏼 Help your partner with more/less lift depending on their level (let them work for it too!)
👊🏼 You only need to apply a gentle assistance (don't think you need to carry their whole weight!)
👊🏼 Use this when you are learning your very first chin up or even if you can do lots but just need help for your last few reps! (Chin ups to failure)
This was a huge help when I wanted to improve my over grip chin up strength...as you get better, ask your partner to only assist when you are struggling 😉 With a bit of practice each week, you will be chin-uping in no time! 😃 Good luck fam!

👟🌾HILL SPRINTS

My favourite type of running! 😊 If you're like me & running distance makes you feel like this👉😩 hills are a fun way to incorporate runs in your weekly fitness

Try adding 10 sprints to the end of your body weight circuit or mix it into your session 👇like I do

3 ROUNDS

x20 push ups
x30 squats
x40 sit-ups
1min plank
x3 hill sprints

Teaching points ❗️ make each sprint MAXIMUM effort 👊 Use a stop watch to time each run to keep it consistent ⌚️ try and beat your best time on the last one! 😁

Depending on the type of exercise you are doing 🏀🏃👟 WHEN you stretch may have different effects on your performance

STATIC stretching (when you hold a stretch for a length of time) before exercise, can reduce performance, especially in explosive & quick movements. Tightness can help to produce better speed & agility, so if you are planning on sprinting, jumping or playing sport, DYNAMIC stretching (stretching with movement, like leg swings, arm circles etc) is a great way to warm up your mobility without hindering your performance

Static stretching still has its place however, it is an important way to improve your flexibility & help with muscle recovery. Save your long stretching for the end of your session when your muscles are nice and warm and enjoy the gentle cool down ☺️

Sometimes it feels like you are going nowhere. You have put in the hard work day in and day out, but it feels like you are in the exact same place you started.
Understand that EVERY positive step you take, every workout, every healthy meal is worth it. There are thousands of amazing changes going on a lot deeper than what you see on the outside.
Change takes time. It may seem like many success stories you hear about happened overnight, but if you read between the lines it's a whole different story. It took a whole year for her to lose that extra weight and get in the habit of exercising everyday, it took him 8 months to run 10km without stopping, it took her 6 failed attempts to give up soft drink...
Never give up. The change is coming. Trust the effort you are putting in everyday, and know that all of the amazing changes on the inside will eventually shine through on the outside ✨

Finding balance ⚖
Physical strength & flexibility are two parts of your fitness that are hard to keep consistent..when you get strong, usually your flexibility suffers 💪🏼😕 BUT it's possible to have both!
The key is matching your stretching time to your workout time ⏰ If you workout everyday, you should be stretching everyday! ✔️☀️
Niggling injuries? Don't recover well after tough sessions? Don't sleep well? or struggling to keep good technique when you workout?! You're probably not stretching enough!
✨TIP!✨
When I run short on time to stretch after my workout, I make it up in the evening in front of the TV! 📺☺️ A little bit everyday (15-30min) is way more effective then one or two huge stretching sessions a week...you with thrive off consistency!! 😃
Happy stretching fam! 😘

Getting sore wrists in your plank? 😫
Make sure you keep nice and strong in your upper body, almost like your back (between your shoulder blades) is lifting towards the sky! ☁️☁️☁️
TIPS❗️
👉🏼Pull your shoulders away from your ears (long neck)
👉🏼Keep your head in line with your body by looking up and out in front of you
👉🏼and...most importantly, press your fingertips into the ground! Like you are trying to grip it! (It will automatically decrease the excess weight in your wrist joint!)

So I got a message yesterday asking how I keep motivated...or how I get extra motivated when I feel like I'm in a slump.
The most effective motivational tool that you will ever have is a PLAN OF ACTION 📝✅
It's great to have an idea of what you want to achieve with your fitness, but how are you going to get there? If you have followed me for a while, you know I am all about taking small positive steps each day. KNOWING what steps you need to take is your biggest motivation (this is your plan!!)...so for me personally I break it down into what I want to achieve on a daily basis (in the next 24hrs) ⏰ I plan time to workout at least once in the day💪🏼 have a minimum of 2 really health meals🍴🍅 and spend some time stretching/doing yoga (my me time)🙆🏼 I know these three things are very achievable and will make me feel accomplished, happy, and on track for that day (anything extra I do on top of this, is a bonus! and I feel really proud that I did it ☺️).
Whenever you start to feel a little off track, brush up on that plan of yours! It doesn't need to be anything dramatic or overwhelming...just a few positive things to take you forward in the next 24hrs ☺️ and make sure you take the time to review how your plan went and acknowledge your achievements at the end of the day...tick them off the list, say them out loud ('I achieved ........ today') , or tell someone what you achieved..anything to help celebrate your efforts! Because you deserve recognition! 😃🙌🏼
Happy planning fam! 😘

I’m going to try my best to write this.
On Thursday night Charlie had an accident. We rushed her to the emergency vet and found out she had badly injured her back. She couldn’t use her back legs and she was trembling in pain.
Charlie had to go into spinal surgery on Friday morning. Although the surgery went really well, they found she had ruptured a disc which had caused her spinal cord to swell. They told us that she had a 50/50 chance she would either begin to recover slowly or that her spinal cord would start to ‘melt’ (which means we would have to let her go).
It’s been the most painful 24hrs. The feeling of not knowing is excruciating. To think that 2 completely different outcomes can happen at any moment has broken us to a point I can’t explain.
BUT, this morning we got a call from the surgeon who told us that Charlie had really good feeling in her back legs, a very positive sign ☺️
We aren’t completely out of it yet, but Charlie is fighting 💪🏼
I wanted to share this with you because you guys have seen her grow up here. I get messages and comments about her all the time and I know you guys care and love her too 🙏🏼 She is my shadow, she does EVERYTHING with me (as I know you have seen from my posts and stories), and I love her more than words can explain.
Thank you to our family and friends for sending their love and healing vibes ♥️ it’s working, she feels it..and I know she will keep fighting 👊🏼
I love you my little Charlie Bear ♥️♥️ Mum, Daddy and Willow are waiting for cuddles as soon as you’re ready 👩🏼👱🏼‍♂️🐶🐶 x

Getting my bell on! 💪🔔 KETTLE-BELL REVERSE LUNGES. 👊Challenge balance, core & shoulder stability, & work those legs & booty!👊 Hold the bell above the head with the left arm.
Step back wide with the right leg.
Squeeze the front knee out as you lunge down, suck the belly button in & keep the bicep next to the ear.
Stand up, step the feet back together.
Continue your reps on the same leg.
Then change sides 😊
If you don't have a bell you can always use a bottle of milk or backpack full of some heavy stuff! 😜

Lunge baby, lunge! 💪💪

Something I learned as an elite athlete was how much my core strength effected not only my performance👟but how it protected me from injury

All of your movements are a chain reaction running though your body ♻️ The lower back is the centre of this chain & is often a weak point (low back pain😩) Building strong muscles around that area stabilises and protects your back while letting the⚡️energy⚡️you create during movement pass effortlessly through your body

Basically, you will feel super
✅EFFECTIVE 💪STRONG &💥POWERFUL

So let's work that core baby!!👊😁 ab❤️x

A rainy morning stretch to relax the back of the legs and lower back ☁️💦☁️💦 1⃣Have toes pointing slightly ⬅️outward➡️ and hold with hands on the ground under the head first. 2⃣Grip outside of the ankles and try to pull the head closer to the ground⬇️. 3⃣Push sitting bones (your bottom 😜) to the roof⬆️. Repeat the same 3 steps with toes pointing ➡️inward⬅️ this should stretch more down the outside of the legs and calf 🐮

Happy stretching! 💙😘

My 5 secrets to get you out of bed for that early morning workout 😁💪🏼...
👉🏼 Make sure your window blinds/curtains aren't fully closed..natural morning light will stimulate your body to wake up ☀️
👉🏼 Lay out your workout clothes the night before (or better yet, wear them to bed!)..no wasting time getting ready when you wake up! 👟
👉🏼 Set your alarm (keep the volume loud!) and put it on the other side of the room..that way you actually have to get up out of bed to turn it off! ⏰
👉🏼 Write your fitness goal, a quote, or get a picture that motivates you and place it next to your alarm...it'll be the first thing you see when you eventually turn that alarm off 📝
👉🏼 Give yourself half a chance of an early morning wake up by getting a good nights sleep..bedtime routine is key! Dim the lights in your house (tells your body it's almost time to sleep), minimise TV, computers, phones etc 30min before bedtime, brush your teeth/shower/pj's (or workout clothes😉), have a gentle stretch (use this to clear your mind too!) then hop into bed when you are ready (when I first lay in bed, I count 10 deep, long breaths in and out..it puts me straight to sleep!) 🌙✨

👊STRETCHING TO IMPROVE SPORTING PERFORMANCE

Stretching was a critical element in my training as an elite pole vaulter 👟 ...mind the face! 😝 haha

Stretching
✅ improves your mobility to help you perform good sporting technique
✅ helps your body to handle training better
✅ encourages quicker recovery &
✅ helps to avoid both sudden and nagging injuries

You don't have to be an athlete to benefit either! 💪 Incorporating daily stretching will improve your personal fitness training in the same way! 😃

'Have I always been flexible?'
This is a question I get asked ALOT so, I thought I would tell you the story... 😊
When I was 3 my dad put me into gymnastics, pretty much because I was crazy and needed to release all of my excess energy 😬 I fell in love with it and I fell in love with training. Dad told me I wasn't the most flexible kid but I worked really hard and would even stretch and practise like crazy at home everyday before and after practise...by the time I was competing (at 6yrs old) I was pretty flexible and it was a strong aspect of my gymnastics (being tall and lanky I definitely wasn't powerful! 😝)
I competed until I was 18 and then I found my way into pole vault. As I tried to get stronger and began to do more weights and strength exercises (rather than stretching) I lost some of my flexibility. I can definitely say it is hard to be really strong and really flexible unless you train both a lot! After years of being a professional pole vaulter I eventually had to retire (due to chronic fatigue) and lost the ability to do any training at all.
After almost a year of detraining and focusing solely on getting healthy I thought I would try yoga, simply because I wanted to move my body again and I thought it would be a good first step.
To cut a long story short, when I first stated yoga I had lost so much flexibility because I hadn't been moving my body, stretching or training for a long time. As time went on, I used yoga as a way to give myself new purpose and new goals. Not only did I aim to get more flexible to achieve all those awesome poses but I started to realise how it made me feel, physically and mentally.
Now I do some form of yoga or stretching everyday, and yes, I have my flexibility back (yay!) but more importantly I FEEL amazing. Stretching is one of the best forms of rehab for your body and it is something we should ALL do regularly (of not everyday!)
No matter how old you are, what your body looks like, or how flexible you are right now every time you stretch you are helping your body. The more you do it, the better you will feel. Simple as that. AND yes you will get flexible!
No time invested in yourself is ever wasted ❤️

💪 BEGINNER CHIN-UPS

Chin ups are one of my favourite exercises! I know they can be pretty daunting sometimes and may even seem impossible 😩
BUT this is a great way to start building strength for your chin up! Wether you can do 10 or you haven't mastered one yet

Jumping up then lowering down as slowly as possible until your arms are straight

TIPS
✅ keep your neck long (don't hunch your shoulders)
✅ squeeze your shoulder blades together and down your back
✅ FULL REPS. All the way up (chin over bar) all the way down (elbows straight) even if you do full chins on your own!
✅ do as many reps as you can at the same slow pace. The slower the better

As soon as you feel you can't keep up the quality, rest actively by doing bent knee windscreen wipers 👉at the end of the video

5 ROUNDS
💥Max beginner chin ups
💥10 x windscreen wipers

👉🏼Hamstring+Splits Stretches👈🏼
.
KNEELING HAMSTRING
• Think 'belly button to thigh' to isolate the stretch into your hamstring!
• Pull your toes up to the sky to increase the stretch and to get even deeper, slowly dip your head (keep belly button to thigh!)
.
SPLITS
• Shuffle your legs slowly into your splits. I always try to do this on grass/carpet/yoga mat so there is padding for my back knee!! Ouch! 😑
• Aim to point both front hip bones forward, if you find this tough, you may need to stretch your hip flexors more thoroughly..
• If you are flat in your splits, try the forward fold/back reach progression
• Come out of your splits SLOWLY..wether you are flat or in a kneeling position, lean to the side and swing your back leg around ☺️
.
👉🏼👉🏼Hold each of your stretches and progressions for AT LEAST 10 deep breaths in and out 😌 Concentrating on your breathing will also make your streatching more comfortable and wayyyyy more enjoyable!! 🙌🏼
Happy Stretching!! 😘

Intense workouts call for enhanced hydration 💦💦
Anyone who knows me knows I sweat like CRAZY when I work out! 😅 Staying ontop of hydration has always been a key component of my training. A hydrated body not only allows you to work harder throughout your workout, you also feel better long after you’ve left the gym, and even recover better!
🙌🏼
When you sweat, you lose more than just water 💦 Good hydration means replacing what you’ve lost, including electrolytes (sodium & potassium), which maintain hydration at cellular level, and B vitamins that help your body metabolise energy 👊🏼💥

Chia puddings by massive babe @earthyandy 😍🍇🍌🍓
When I worked as a PT doing late nights all week I used to make a whole stack of these for the week so I could have them as a quick dinner when training my clients 💪🏼😁
It's super easy!
👉🏼 Find some containers/jars and put 3 TABLESPOONS of chia seeds in each.
👉🏼 Use your favourite milk (soy, almond, coconut, regular etc) and pour in 1CUP and stir.
👉🏼 Put them in the fridge and they will be ready overnight! 🌙✨ (I usually made 4-5 jars and they lasted all week ☺️)
Oooooo if you want to add more flavour and texture I also stir in some chopped dried fruit like mango and cranberries, and whole nuts like walnuts and almonds! You can also put fresh fruit on top too!! 🍓 Soooo good! 👌🏼
Chia is a great source of protein! 💪🏼 So this is an awesome post workout snack option too ☺️

Lunges. A great way to progress from squats and really challenge leg strength and balance. I've just started to put these back into my training program to change things up again 😊 ❕In any type of lunge there are a few important key points❕

1⃣ keep your weight in the heel of the front foot at all times
2⃣ don't let the front knee move forward past the line of the toe
3⃣ squeeze the front knee out in line with the pinky toe on the way down and up

Start with both feet on the ground while you build strength in the movement then you can work up to this variation with the back foot lifted to add an extra challenge!

3 x10 each leg..Get those legs and glutes burning!! 🔥😁

Hands up those of you feeling overwhelmed or highly stressed lately? 😖 I want you to keep reading because this post is for you!
Over this last week, I personally have had just wayyy to much in my plate and it's been feeling like I've been swallowed up by a to-do list and I just can't escape! (Sound familiar for anyone?!) ☹️
I'm going to keep this simple and tell you ONE thing that has helped me over the last couple of days..
Before I go to bed, I stretch. It sounds basic but I can't tell you how much this simple thing has kept me together!
There is a special routine I do and I want to share it with you ☺️👇🏼
⭐️ Shower, pj's, brush teeth and find a quiet room
⭐️ Light some candles for some natural light
⭐️ Turn off anything electronic, lights, TV, phone, computer (except if you're a music person, find your favourite relaxed music)
⭐️ Settle down, enjoy the dimmed light and go through your favourite stretches (especially your hips, they hold the most tension!)
⭐️ Whenever you feel your ready, stumble into bed
You may stretch for 10min, or you could take an hour..whatever you feel you need. Stretching releases hormones that encourage your body (and brain!) to relax, the dimmed light and minimal electrics calm your nervous system, and time to slow down and focus only on stretching your muscles will clear your mind and encourage restful sleep (the most essential time for repair and rejuvenation).
I want you to try it. Even if your not overly stressed, you will still be amazed by how much this simple way to end your day will change the way you function entirely! 🙏🏼✨
Happy stretching fam 😘

Flowing alongside nature’s greatness 🙌🏼 After this incredible sunset, I went home and finally watched ‘Before The Flood’ 🌿🎥 if you haven’t seen it yet, YOU NEED TO.
🌏 Our earth is crying out for help.
The devastation mankind has made on our home is unbearable 😔 During our short time here, we have consumed, polluted, and destroyed every ecosystem more than any other species on this planet.
We need to change.
It might seem overwhelming, and you might think you don’t have any influence or power to make a difference. BUT YOU DO.
As a race, we influence each other. With our beliefs, our voices, and most importantly our actions 👊🏼
WHAT CAN YOU DO TODAY TO HELP OUR FRAGILE WORLD? 🌍
👉🏼Turn off lights & appliances if you aren’t using them. Even at the power point!💡
👉🏼Dry your clothes on the line, rather than the dryer 👕
👉🏼Walk or ride your bike as much as you can instead of using the car 🚲
👉🏼Eat less beef. It is one of the biggest causes of greenhouse gases and requires the most amount of land to produce. (in the US, of all the land used for food production, 70% is used to grow feed for cattle. 1% is used to grow crops for humans) 🐂
👉🏼Avoid products that use palm oil. Palm oil is a major cause of deforestation 🌳
👉🏼Use a reusable keep cup for your take away coffee. Take away coffee cups can’t be recycled 😔
👉🏼Vote for people who support climate action 👏🏼
👉🏼Use reusable grocery bags 🛍
👉🏼Recycle! ♻️
👉🏼and don’t be afraid to TALK & SHARE! Teach your kids, chat with your friends and family, get environmental friendly initiatives happening at work, and most importantly lead by example.
WE CAN MAKE A CHANGE 👊🏼 TOGETHER.
Every positive effort makes a difference for ourselves, and for the generations to come ♥️

Deadlifts at the gym today! 🙌🏼 @goodlifehc
Deadlifts are all about activating your 'back chain' muscles (hamstrings, glutes) and of course your core to stabilise 💪🏼
TIPS!!
👉🏼 Set up correctly by standing feet hip width apart, bend at the hips to reach the bar and think 'butt back and back straight' (if this is tough you probably have tight hamstrings!)
👉🏼 BEFORE you lift the bar, press the bar against your shins, pull your shoulders away from your ears (this will engage your upper back), sit back on your heels and look down at the ground in front of you.
👉🏼 DURING your lift, guide the bar along your shins (like you are shaving), keep the bar moving along your entire leg until you get to standing. Squeeze your butt at the top!
👉🏼 As you lower, push your butt back, bend at the hips, and keep your back straight (notice I am looking down at the ground during my entire lift to maintain straight spine).
👉🏼 Your weight should be in your heels and you should not feel any pain in your lower back! Start light (even with just a broomstick!) and focus on excellent technique 👌🏼

Missing a workout, having a bad meal, or getting off track doesn't mean it's all over! It's funny how sometimes we think it has to be all or nothing.
'I need to do it perfectly otherwise it's not going to work!' 'I can't miss a day!' 'I didn't do it right, I need to start again!' 👈🏼 This, is definitely not true..Yes you need to put in the hard work, yes you need to have discipline, yes you need to do things the best you can. BUT when you don't, it doesn't mean you have ruined all of the progress you have made.
It's about being consistent. Even on your bad days. Ok, so you slipped up. That's done now. Ask yourself 'what's ONE thing I can do next that will get me back on track?'
We are never going to have a perfect track record. It's about outweighing the slip ups, with positive effort in the right direction...that's how we move forward 👊🏼

Let's talk SHIN SPLINTS!
If you run a lot or do lots of workouts incorporating jumping & plyometrics you might have had this before..I had them quite badly one season as a pole vaulter and it's the worst!! 😫
Shin splints is pain on the inside of your shin bone (your tibia) caused by a number of things including: a sudden increase in intensity or frequency of training, weak muscles in your core, lower leg & feet, bad shoes, poor training technique & sometimes a combination of all these things!
Inflexibility of your calf muscle will overload and start pulling on the shin bone causing more pain 😥 ouch!!
TREATMENT:
The best is to try a combination of:
🔸Rest and avoiding any exercises that aggravate (also ice to reduce pain & swelling!)
🔸Stretching and self massage to release the calf (especially near the shin bone) and arch of the foot
🔸Shoes! You need good support & cushioning for your foot, maybe it's time for new ones!
🔸Strengthening your calf & foot muscles (walking/running in sand helped me)
🔸Lastly, professional sports massage and acupuncture was one of the best treatments that helped release my calf muscles
BUT..remember prevention is always better than treatment!! Have a look at your running technique, stretch regularly, change your shoes regularly (at least every 6months), build good core strength (including deep core & glutes!) and incorporate good recovery sessions (yoga, beach, massage etc)! ☺️😘
